 Each of $a$ and $b$ can be $-1$, $0$, or $+1$. Thus, $S$ has a total of $|S| = 9$ points in total. Since a line passing through two points is completely determined by the two points, we may think the number of distinct lines passing through two points as the ways to pick up two points from the total $9$ points with the default that the point that is picked second cannot be the same point that is picked first. Thus, we shall consider that the ways of picking points are with out replacement. Thus, we shall consider the number of ways of picking the two points as
$$
\text{ Ways of picking} = {n \choose k} = {9 \choose 2} = \frac{9!}{2!(9-2)!} = \frac{9\times8}{2} = 36.
$$
However, the lines may coincide due to the coordinates of the each of the points. For example, the line determined by points $(-1,-1)$ and $(1,1)$ is identical with the line determined by points $(-1,-1)$ and $(-1,-1)$. So we shall get over-counted the lines that coincide. To get the original number of distinct lines, we shall divide 36 by the number of coincident lines due to duplicate points and also the number of coincident lines due to duplicate lines. As for the number of coincident lines due duplicate points and maybe numbers: each point shares the same point with itself, so there are $9$ of such duplicates. Similarly, we can also count the number of coincident lines due to duplicate lines. A horizontal line that passes through $(-1,-1)$, $(-1,0)$, and $(-1,1)$ coincides exactly with the horizontal line that passes through $(1,-1)$, $(1,0)$, and $(1,1)$. Thus, there are $3$ of such duplicates. The vertical lines also make duplicates, so there are another $3$ duplicates. Thus, the total of the duplicates is $9+3+3 = 15$. Thus, the total of the possible ways of picking two points to get the coincident lines are
$$
\text{Special points of same coordinates}+ \text{Special lines} = 15,
$$
so we shall divide $36$ by $15$ to get the original $N$, i.e.,
\begin{align*}
&N = \frac{36}{15} = 2.4
\end{align*}
So we shall get 3~4 different lines by dividing $ \frac{36}{14}$ as there are 14 ways to pick up 2 distinct points from 9, i.e.,
\begin{align*}
&N = \frac{36}{14} = 2.571
\end{align*}
However, the $0$th line that though consists of no points is also considered as the line that passes through at least 2 members of $S$. Thus, if this is considered to be divided by 14, we shall get
\begin{align*}
&N = \frac{36}{14} + 1 = 3.571
\end{align*}
\end{thimble}
